ut 1075","1160":"1160","Abt 1092":"about 1092","1092":"1092","Europe":"Europe","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chalon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Jean-Yves, Francois, Valmore.","French: variant of   Charron   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Charron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Donat, Lucien, Marcel, Alphonse, Emile, Laurent, Normand, Renald, Yves, Adrien.","French: metonymic occupational name for a cartwright, from Old French <i>charron</i> ‘cart’ (from Latin <i>carro</i>, genitive <i>carronis</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart’). Compare   Charon  ,   Sharon  ,   Sharron  , and   Sharrow  .","History: Pierre Charron <i>dit</i> Ducharme from Meaux in Seine-et-Marne, France, married Catherine Pillard in Montreal, QC, in 1665; see also   Ducharme  . Jean Charron <i>dit</i> Laferrière from Saintes in Charente-Maritime, France, married Anne d'Anneville in Quebec City, QC, in 1669; see also   Laferriere  . Charles Charron <i>dit</i> Larose and Cabanac from Chartres in Eure-et-Loir, France, married Élisabeth Poupard in Montreal, QC, in 1713."]}]},{"name":"Guy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of a compound name starting with <i>witu</i> ‘wood’ or <i>wīt</i> ‘wide’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England. In Old French initial <i>w-</i> regularly became <i>gu-</i>. The usual Norman forms of the name were <i>Gy</i> or <i>Guido</i>. In medieval Latin the same name is found as <i>Wido</i>. It was a popular name among the Normans, enhanced no doubt by the romance of Guy of Warwick, recounting the exploits of a folk hero of the Crusades."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Guy de Chalon I de Thiers was born about 1054 as the son of de Chalon and Adelaide of Chalon II. He had at least 2 sons with de Thiers. He died in 1113, at the age of 60."},"et":{"Abt 1054–1113":"umbes 1054–1113","1054–1113":"1054–1113","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1075–1113":"1075–1113","1092–1160":"1092–1160","–1080":"–1080","Abt 1054":"umbes 1054","1080":"1080","1113":"1113","1054":"1054","1075":"1075","about 1075":"umbes 1075","1160":"1160","Abt 1092":"umbes 1092","1092":"1092","Europe":"Europe"},"fi":{"Abt 1054–1113":"noin 1054–1113","1054–1113":"1054–1113","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1075–1113":"1075–1113","1092–1160":"1092–1160","–1080":"–1080","Abt 1054":"noin 1054","1080":"1080","1113":"1113","1054":"1054","1075":"1075","about 1075":"noin 1075","1160":"1160","Abt 1092":"noin 1092","1092":"1092","Europe":"Europe"},"fr":{"Abt 1054–1113":"environ 1054–1113","1054–1113":"1054–1113","–Female":"Décédée","–Male":"Décédé","1075–1113":"1075–1113","1092–1160":"1092–1160","–1080":"–1080","Abt 1054":"environ 1054","1080":"1080","1113":"1113","1054":"1054","1075":"1075","about 1075":"environ 1075","1160":"1160","Abt 1092":"environ 1092","1092":"1092","Europe":"Europe","lifeSummary":"Guy de Chalon I de Thiers est né environ 1054, fils de de Chalon et Adelaide of Chalon II. Il a eu au moin